<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec124-CrossProduct" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Cross Product</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In the previous section, we learned about the <em>Dot Product</em>, a way to multiply two vectors to get a scalar (a single number). 
      You might be wondering whether there is another way to multiply two vectors? 
    </p>
    <p>
      The answer is yes! 
      We can multiply two vectors in a special way to get a third vector. 
      This is called the <term>Cross Product</term>. 
      However, unlike the dot product which works in any dimension, the cross product is special. 
      It only works meaningfully in <m>\R^3</m>. 
      This operation is incredibly useful for finding orthogonal directions, calculating areas, and understanding rotation in physics.
    </p>

    <objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          After this section, students will be able to:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li><p>compute the cross product of two vectors using determinants.</p></li>
        <li><p>use standard basis properties to simplify cross product calculations.</p></li>
        <li><p>calculate the area of a parallelogram and the volume of a parallelepiped.</p></li>
        <li><p>apply the cross product to physics problems involving torque.</p></li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
  </introduction>

  <p>
    Let's dive right into the definition. 
    The formula can look a bit intimidating at first, but we will use a tool called a <em>determinant</em> to help us remember it.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-CrossProduct">
    <title>The Cross Product</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given two vectors <m>\v{v} = \la v_1, v_2, v_3 \ra</m> and <m>\v{w} = \la w_1, w_2, w_3 \ra</m> in <m>\R^3</m>, the <term>cross product</term> <m>\v{v} \times \v{w}</m> is the vector defined by:
        <me>
          \v{v} \times \v{w} = \la v_2 w_3 - v_3 w_2, -(v_1 w_3 - v_3 w_1), v_1 w_2 - v_2 w_1 \ra
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    Wow this definition looks crazy!  
    No one should memorize this long of a formula! 
    If you know a bit linear algebra, the cross product can be computed using the <alert>determinant</alert>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Given the two vectors <m>\v{v} = \la v_1, v_2, v_3 \ra</m> and <m>\v{w} = \la w_1, w_2, w_3 \ra</m>, we can construct a matrix as follows: 
    <md>
      \begin{pmatrix} 
        \v{i} \amp \v{j} \amp \v{k} \\ 
        v_1 \amp v_2 \amp v_3 \\
        w_1 \amp w_2 \amp w_3
      \end{pmatrix}
    </md>
    where the <m>\v{i}</m>, <m>\v{j}</m>, and <m>\v{k}</m> are the standard basis vectors in <m>\R^3</m>.
  </p>
    
  <p>
    It turns out that the cross product <m>\v{v} \times \v{w}</m> is the <em>determinant</em> of this matrix. 
    That is, 
    <md>
      <mrow>\v{v} \times \v{w} \amp= \begin{vmatrix} \v{i} \amp \v{j} \amp \v{k} \\ v_1 \amp v_2 \amp v_3 \\ w_1 \amp w_2 \amp w_3 \end{vmatrix}</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp= \begin{vmatrix} v_2 \amp v_3 \\ w_2 \amp w_3 \end{vmatrix} \v{i} - \begin{vmatrix} v_1 \amp v_3 \\ w_1 \amp w_3 \end{vmatrix} \v{j} + \begin{vmatrix} v_1 \amp v_2 \\ w_1 \amp w_2 \end{vmatrix} \v{k}</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp= (v_2 w_3 - v_3 w_2)\v{i} - (v_1 w_3 - v_3 w_1)\v{j} + (v_1 w_2 - v_2 w_1)\v{k}</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp= \la v_2 w_3 - v_3 w_2, -(v_1 w_3 - v_3 w_1), v_1 w_2 - v_2 w_1 \ra</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    P.S.: Yes Richard did a cofactor expansion on the first row in his work above. 
    Remember that this isn't really a linear algebra class so he will not go in depth on the cofactor expansion. 
    If linear algebra isn't your thing and you don't want to memorize the formula (no one should), you can find the determine of a 3x3 matrix using the lattice method. 
    Below is a quick video tutorial on how to do that: 
  </p>

  <figure>
    <caption>Quick Tutorial on Computing the Determinant of a 3x3 Matrix</caption>
    <video youtube="WLY8hg63TU0" width="50%"/>
  </figure>

  <example>
    <p>
      Compute <m>\v{v} \times \v{w}</m> for <m>\v{v} = \la 1, 2, -1 \ra</m> and <m>\v{w} = \la 3, 0, 1 \ra</m>.
    </p>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\v{v} \times \v{w} \amp= \begin{vmatrix} \v{i} \amp \v{j} \amp \v{k} \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ 3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \begin{vmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} \v{i} - \begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 3 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} \v{j} + \begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 0 \end{vmatrix} \v{k} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= (2 \cdot 1 - (-1) \cdot 0)\v{i} - (1 \cdot 1 - (-1) \cdot 3)\v{j} + (1 \cdot 0 - 2 \cdot 3)\v{k} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= (2 - 0)\v{i} - (1 + 3)\v{j} + (0 - 6)\v{k} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= 2\v{i} - 4\v{j} - 6\v{k} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \la 2, -4, -6 \ra </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Below is a quick sketch to visualize the two vectors and their cross product. 
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-cross-product-example">
        <caption>Visualizing <m>\v{v} \times \v{w}</m> for <m>\v{v}=\la 1,2,-1 \ra</m> and <m>\v{w}=\la 3,0,1 \ra</m></caption>
        <sidebyside width="80%">
          <interactive platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
            <slate surface="sage">
              var('x,y,z')

              # 1. Define the vectors
              v = vector([1, 2, -1])
              w = vector([3, 0, 1])

              # 2. Calculate the Cross Product
              cp = v.cross_product(w)

              # 3. Create the Arrows (Vectors)
              # Blue for v, Green for w, Red for Result
              vec_v = arrow3d((0,0,0), v, color='blue', width=2)
              vec_w = arrow3d((0,0,0), w, color='green', width=2)
              vec_cp = arrow3d((0,0,0), cp, color='red', width=3) 

              # 4. Add Labels
              label_v = text3d("v", v + vector([0, 0.2, 0]), color='blue')
              label_w = text3d("w", w + vector([0, 0, 0.2]), color='green')
              label_cp = text3d("v x w", cp + vector([0.2, 0, 0]), color='red')

              # 5. Setup Coordinate Axes
              # We need to extend the z-axis down since the result is (2, -4, -6)
              axes = arrow3d((0,0,0), (4,0,0), color='black') + \
                    arrow3d((0,0,0), (0,3,0), color='black') + \
                    arrow3d((0,0,0), (0,0,2), color='black') + \
                    arrow3d((0,0,0), (0,0,-7), color='gray') # Negative z-axis

              axis_labels = text3d("x", (4.2, 0, 0), color='black') + \
                            text3d("y", (0, 3.2, 0), color='black') + \
                            text3d("z", (0, 0, 2.2), color='black')

              # 6. Show everything
              show(vec_v + vec_w + vec_cp + label_v + label_w + label_cp + axes + axis_labels, frame=False)
            </slate>
          </interactive>
        </sidebyside>
      </figure>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
    Now that we know how the cross product works, let's explore some of its important properties! 
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-CrossPropertiesBasis">
    <title>Properties of the Cross Product</title>

    <p>
      Let's start off by observing the behavior of the cross product in the <xref ref="fig-cross-product-example"/>. 
      The most obvious observation here is that <m>\v{v} \times \v{w}</m> is also a vector! 
    </p>

    <p>
      We can also see that <m>\v{v} \times \v{w}</m> is orthogonal to both <m>\v{v}</m> and <m>\v{w}</m>. 
      It turns out that the cross product always produces a vector that is perpendicular to both input vectors, following the <term>right-hand rule</term>, 
      which states that <em>when the fingers of your right hand curl from <m>\v{v}</m> to <m>\v{w}</m>, your thumb points to the same side of the plane spanned by <m>\v{v}</m> and <m>\v{w}</m> as their cross product</em>. 
    </p>

    <figure>
      <image source="sec124_RightHandRule_CrossProduct.png" width="50%"></image>
      <caption>Right-Hand Rule for Cross Product</caption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Other than these geometric properties, the cross product also has several algebraic properties that are useful in computations. 
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-BasicPropertiesCrossProduct">
      <title>Basic Properties of the Cross Product</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ol marker="i.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\v{w} \times \v{v} = -\v{v} \times \v{w}</m> (Anticommutative Property)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\v{v} \times \v{v} = \v{0}</m> (Cross Product with Itself is Zero)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\v{v} \times \v{w} = \v{0}</m> if and only if either <m>\v{w} = \lambda\v{v}</m> for some scalar <m>\lambda</m> or <m>\v{v} = \v{0}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(\lambda\v{v}) \times \v{w}  = \v{v} \times (\lambda\v{w}) = \lambda(\v{v} \times \v{w})</m> (Scalar Multiplication)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\lp \v{u} + \v{v} \rp \times \v{w} = \v{u} \times \v{w} + \v{v} \times \v{w}</m>
              </p>
              <p>
                <m>\v{u} \times \lp \v{v} + \v{w} \rp = \v{u} \times \v{v} + \v{u} \times \v{w}</m> (Distributive Property)
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      Some of the results can be justified directly from the right-hand rule and geometric intuition. 
      For example, the anticommutative property makes sense because switching the order of the vectors reverses the direction of the resulting vector.
      As a mathematician, we should also verify these properties using the definition of the cross product (the one with the determinant). 
    </p>

    <proof>
      <title>Some Proofs of Cross Product Properties</title>
      <p>
        Richard will prove some of these properties using the determinant definition of the cross product.
        Some will be left as exercises for the reader. 
        <ol marker="i.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\v{v} = \la v_1, v_2, v_3 \ra</m> and <m>\v{w} = \la w_1, w_2, w_3 \ra</m>. 
              Then we obtain
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  \v{w} \times \v{v} \amp= \begin{vmatrix} \v{i} \amp \v{j} \amp \v{k} \\ w_1 \amp w_2 \amp w_3 \\ v_1 \amp v_2 \amp v_3 \end{vmatrix}
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp= (w_2 v_3 - w_3 v_2)\v{i} - (w_1 v_3 - w_3 v_1)\v{j} + (w_1 v_2 - w_2 v_1)\v{k}
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp= -(v_2 w_3 - v_3 w_2)\v{i} + (v_1 w_3 - v_3 w_1)\v{j} - (v_1 w_2 - v_2 w_1)\v{k}
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp= - \left[ (v_2 w_3 - v_3 w_2)\v{i} - (v_1 w_3 - v_3 w_1)\v{j} + (v_1 w_2 - v_2 w_1)\v{k} \right]
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp= - (\v{v} \times \v{w})
                </mrow>
              </md>
              Thus, the cross product is anticommutative.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\v{v} = \la v_1, v_2, v_3 \ra</m>. 
              Then we have
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  \v{v} \times \v{v} \amp= \begin{vmatrix} \v{i} \amp \v{j} \amp \v{k} \\ v_1 \amp v_2 \amp v_3 \\ v_1 \amp v_2 \amp v_3 \end{vmatrix}
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp= \la v_2 v_3 - v_3 v_2, -(v_1 v_3 - v_3 v_1), v_1 v_2 - v_2 v_1 \ra
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp= \la 0, -0, 0 \ra
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp= \v{0}
                </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Left as an exercise to the reader.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Left as an exercise to the reader.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Left as an exercise to the reader.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      
    </proof>
    
    <p>
      The most fun thing about the cross product is how it interacts with the standard basis vectors in <m>\R^3</m>. 
      Recall the standard basis vectors are <m>\v{i} = \la 1,0,0 \ra</m>, <m>\v{j} = \la 0,1,0 \ra</m>, and <m>\v{k} = \la 0,0,1 \ra</m>. 
      Because these are orthogonal unit vectors, following the right-hand rule, we have a cyclic pattern:
    </p>
    
    <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\v{i} \times \v{j} \amp = \v{k}</mrow>
          <mrow>\v{j} \times \v{k} \amp = \v{i}</mrow>
          <mrow>\v{k} \times \v{i} \amp = \v{j}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
      If you reverse the order, you get the negative (anticommutative):
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\v{j} \times \v{i} \amp = -\v{k}</mrow>
          <mrow>\v{k} \times \v{j} \amp = -\v{i}</mrow>
          <mrow>\v{i} \times \v{k} \amp = -\v{j}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
      The following circle summarizes these properties:
    </p>
    
    <figure>
      <image source="sec124-CircleCrossProduct-Diagram.png" width="35%"></image>
      <caption>Circle for Computing the Cross Product of Standard Basis Vectors</caption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      If you don't mind some FOIL-ing and combining like terms, you can actually use this circle to compute the cross product instead of the determinant! 
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Calculate the cross product <m>\lp 3\v{i} - \v{j} - 2\v{k}\rp \times \lp 3\v{j} - 2\v{k} \rp</m>. 
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> \lp 3\v{i} - \v{j} - 2\v{k}\rp \times \lp 3\v{j} - 2\v{k} \rp\amp= 9\v{i} \times \v{j} - 6\v{i} \times \v{k} - 3\v{j} \times \v{j} + 2\v{j} \times \v{k} - 6\v{k} \times \v{k} + 4\v{k} \times \v{k}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 9\v{k} - 6(-\v{j}) - 3(0) + 2(-\v{i}) - 6(0) + 4(0)</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp= 9\v{k} + 6\v{j} - 2\v{i}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      This is actually how the determinant formula is derived! 
      If we write <m>\v{v} = v_1\v{i} + v_2\v{j} + v_3\v{k}</m> and <m>\v{w} = w_1\v{i} + w_2\v{j} + w_3\v{k}</m> and expand <m>\v{v} \times \v{w}</m> like a polynomial, we can use the rules above to simplify the terms.
    </p>

    <note>
      <title>If you want to see a bunch of letters here to derive the formula...</title>
      <p>
        To be a due diligent mathematician, Richard will show you how to derive the determinant formula from the standard basis properties (and there are a lot of the typing here...). 
      </p>

      <p>
        Let <m>\v{v} = v_1\v{i} + v_2\v{j} + v_3\v{k}</m> and <m>\v{w} = w_1\v{i} + w_2\v{j} + w_3\v{k}</m>. 
        Then we have
        <md>
          <mrow>\v{v} \times \v{w} \amp= \lp v_1\v{i} + v_2\v{j} + v_3\v{k} \rp \times \lp w_1\v{i} + w_2\v{j} + w_3\v{k} \rp</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= v_1w_1 \underbrace{\lp \v{i} \times \v{i} \rp}_{\v{0}} + v_1w_2 \underbrace{\lp \v{i} \times \v{j} \rp}_{\v{k}} + v_1w_3 \underbrace{\lp \v{i} \times \v{k} \rp}_{-\v{j}}</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp \qquad + v_2w_1 \underbrace{\lp \v{j} \times \v{i} \rp}_{-\v{k}} + v_2w_2 \underbrace{\lp \v{j} \times \v{j} \rp}_{\v{0}} + v_2w_3 \underbrace{\lp \v{j} \times \v{k} \rp}_{\v{i}}</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp \qquad + v_3w_1 \underbrace{\lp \v{k} \times \v{i} \rp}_{\v{j}} + v_3w_2 \underbrace{\lp \v{k} \times \v{j} \rp}_{-\v{i}} + v_3w_3 \underbrace{\lp \v{k} \times \v{k} \rp}_{\v{0}}</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= (v_2w_3 - v_3w_2)\v{i} - (v_1w_3 - v_3w_1)\v{j} + (v_1w_2 - v_2w_1)\v{k}</mrow>
        </md>
        
      </p>
    </note>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-AreaGeometry">
    <title>Geometry: Area of a Parallelogram</title>

    <p>
      We know the direction of <m>\v{u} \times \v{v}</m> is orthogonal to the inputs (given by the Right Hand Rule). But what about its <em>magnitude</em>?
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-CrossMagnitude">
      <title>Magnitude of the Cross Product</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <me>\|\v{u} \times \v{v}\| = \|\v{u}\| \|\v{v}\| \sin(\theta)</me>
          where <m>\theta</m> is the angle between the vectors.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      The proof of this theorem is at the end of the section in your textbook, so Richard will not repeat it here. 
      It requires an identity that links the dot product and cross product together. 
      Feel free to read through it later if you are interested! 
    </p>

    <p>
      Geometrically, this value represents the <strong>Area of the Parallelogram</strong> spanned by the two vectors. 
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>The magnitude of the cross product equals the area of the shaded parallelogram.</caption>
      <sidebyside width="80%">
      <interactive platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <slate surface="sage">
          var('x,y,z')
          # Define vectors
          u = vector([3, 0, 0])
          v = vector([1, 2, 0])
          
          # Compute cross product for visual context (not plotted directly here to keep it clean)
          cp = u.cross_product(v)
          
          # Plot vectors
          vec_u = arrow3d((0,0,0), u, color='blue', width=3)
          vec_v = arrow3d((0,0,0), v, color='red', width=3)
          
          # Parallelogram edges
          edge_u = arrow3d(v, v+u, color='blue', width=1, arrowsize=1) # Parallel to u
          edge_v = arrow3d(u, u+v, color='red', width=1, arrowsize=1) # Parallel to v
          
          # Fill the parallelogram (Polygon)
          poly = polygon3d([(0,0,0), u, u+v, v], color='yellow', opacity=0.4)
          
          # Labels
          labels = text3d("u", u/2 + vector([0,-0.2,0]), color='blue') + \
                   text3d("v", v/2 + vector([-0.2,0.2,0]), color='red') + \
                   text3d("Area = ||u x v||", (u+v)/2, color='black')
                   
          axes = arrow3d((0,0,0), (4,0,0), color='black') + \
                 arrow3d((0,0,0), (0,4,0), color='black') + \
                 arrow3d((0,0,0), (0,0,2), color='black')
          
          show(vec_u + vec_v + edge_u + edge_v + poly + labels + axes, frame=False)
        </slate>
      </interactive>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>

    <example>
      <p>
        Find the area of the triangle with vertices <m>P(1,0,0)</m>, <m>Q(3,0,1)</m>, and <m>R(2,2,0)</m>.
      </p>
      <hint>
        <p>
          A triangle is exactly <em>half</em> of a parallelogram. So if we find the area of the parallelogram spanned by vectors <m>\v{PQ}</m> and <m>\v{PR}</m>, we just need to divide by 2!
        </p>
      </hint>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Volume">
    <title>Geometry: Volume of a Parallelepiped</title>

    <p>
      If we add a third vector <m>\v{w}</m>, we lift the 2D parallelogram into a 3D slanted box called a <strong>Parallelepiped</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      To find this volume, we use the <strong>Scalar Triple Product</strong>. Think about it: the area of the base is <m>\|\v{u} \times \v{v}\|</m>. The height of the box is the component of <m>\v{w}</m> in the direction of that normal vector.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-TripleProduct">
      <title>Volume of a Parallelepiped</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The volume <m>V</m> of the parallelepiped determined by vectors <m>\v{u}, \v{v}, \v{w}</m> is the absolute value of the scalar triple product:
          <me>
            V = |\v{w} \cdot (\v{u} \times \v{v})| = \left| \begin{vmatrix} w_1 \amp w_2 \amp w_3 \\ u_1 \amp u_2 \amp u_3 \\ v_1 \amp v_2 \amp v_3 \end{vmatrix} \right|
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <figure>
      <caption>A parallelepiped spanned by vectors u, v, w.</caption>
      <sidebyside width="80%">
      <interactive platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <slate surface="sage">
          var('x,y,z')
          # Vectors
          u = vector([2, 0, 0])
          v = vector([1, 2, 0])
          w = vector([0, 1, 3])
          
          # Vertices of the parallelepiped
          O = vector([0,0,0])
          verts = [O, u, u+v, v, w, w+u, w+u+v, w+v]
          
          # Draw vectors
          vecs = arrow3d(O, u, color='blue', width=3) + \
                 arrow3d(O, v, color='red', width=3) + \
                 arrow3d(O, w, color='green', width=3)
                 
          # Draw the box edges
          box = line3d([O, u, u+v, v, O], color='black') + \
                line3d([w, w+u, w+u+v, w+v, w], color='black') + \
                line3d([O, w], color='black') + \
                line3d([u, w+u], color='black') + \
                line3d([v, w+v], color='black') + \
                line3d([u+v, w+u+v], color='black')

          # Fill slightly
          # (Visualizing the solid is tricky in simple plots, so wireframe is often clearer)
          
          labels = text3d("u", u/2, color='blue') + text3d("v", v/2, color='red') + text3d("w", w/2, color='green')
          
          show(vecs + box + labels, frame=False)
        </slate>
      </interactive>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
  </subsection>

